                  <handDesc>
                     <p>Formal, somewhat ornate book hand. The professional scribe wrote slowly and quite carefully with a thick pen. There is high stop at the end of l. 301, but no other marks of punctuation or lectional signs are visible. Some use of contrast between thick and thin strokes is noticeable, especially in letters which have oblique elements. The stance of the letters, upright to sloping very slightly to the right, is regularly maintained, with ample space being left between letters. The bilinear character of the writing is marked and, so far as can be observed, is violated only by the letter phi. This quality is accentuated by hooks or serifs, often rather prominent ones, which occur usually at the bases, but occasionally at the tops of some letters.</p>
                  </handDesc>
